Ok there is another release on the SharpNEAT web site 
http://www.cgreen.dsl.pipex.com/

This includes a deterministic prey capture evaluator as described in my 
previous email. I normally see this solved within 100,000 evaluations 
(see new eval counter in the GUI) using the default search parameters. 
Once this task is solved the evaluator switches to the old 
non-deterministic approach (random start positions, varying prey initial 
moves and speed) - unfortunately this part didn&#39;t work at all well, I 
didn&#39;t see any improvement, in fact the networks lost some of their old 
ability, presumably because the random trials don&#39;t test every bit of 
functionality and therfore some can be lost from one generation to the 
next.

It did just occur to me though that the non-deterministic trials can be 
made deterministic very easily by resetting the random number generator 
before each set of trials. I just tried this and it does seem to work - 
the best fitness stabilizes whereas before it could be seen to vary - 
but the best fitness now seems stuck at 61 and 63 out of 64 in the two 
trials I am running

Anyway there is a saved network in the zip that performs perfectly on 
the pre-determined tests. In the prey capture evaluator click on the 
&quot;Initialise [Deterministic]&quot;  button - this loops through the 16 start 
positions. If you then set the prey initial moves to 3 and the speed to 
0 and click on the &#39;Step&#39; button to see the deterministic trial.  You 
can of course still run the preycapture simulation automatically but 
this uses random start positions (distance 0-4) and therefore you may 
not see perfect results.

Colin.

