&gt;I&#39;ll probably write up what I did in detail on the web site, just 
&gt;quickly though I had a think about what you said about randomization in 
&gt;the trials, so whereas before I used 100 randomized trials and gradually 
&gt;increased the difficulty by giving the prey 0 to 4 initial moves an then 
&gt;increasing it&#39;s speed, I am now running 32 predefined trials. 16 tests 
&gt;with the prey starting within sensor range and not moving and another 16 
&gt;using the same start positions but allowing the prey 3 initial moves. 
&gt;The initial moves are also deterministic in that the prey moves directly 
&gt;away from the agent and this also has the effect of moving the prey out 
&gt;of sensor range - by then though the agent has received inputs with the 
&gt;prey&#39;s location, so it has chance to remember where they prey was seen. 
&gt;These tests are passed 100% but do not produce a perfect agent - it 
&gt;still can&#39;t chase moving prey with a 4 move head start in all test 
&gt;cases, although it does perform pretty well actually :). Anyway this 
&gt;situation should be resolvable by extending the trials to contain 
&gt;further more difficult tests or by switching completely to a more 
&gt;difficult trial  i.e.incremental evolution.  In fact I may be able to 
&gt;revert to my original randomized trials once a good population has been 
&gt;found.
